        - <script>        empty             vs server-side dereference of
                                              current.case followed by
                                              disjunction of parent-case
                                              assigned_agent / assigned_group
                                              checks
        - <sys_id>        eebbc1bbf1aeab598e7ba377e1e6604b
                                            vs MD5("x_[scope]_case_party.read.case_agent.assigned")
        - <sys_update_name> *_read_manager  vs *_read_agent_assigned
      vs ../acl/x_[scope]_case_read_manager.xml (manager READ on parent
      case table):
        - <name>          x_[scope]_case_party
                                            vs x_[scope]_case
        - <sys_id>        eebbc1bbf1aeab598e7ba377e1e6604b
                                            vs 113c23bfb587d172b83db7ac8961ade2
        - <sys_update_name> *_case_party_read_manager
                                            vs *_case_read_manager
        - <description>                     references case_party table
                                            vs case table
        Both ACLs have identical <operation>=read,
        <roles>=x_[scope]_case_manager, <advanced>=false,
        <condition/>=empty, <script/>=empty - the only differences are
        the table name (case_party vs case) and the deterministic sys_id
        derived from that table name. This parallelism is what
        materializes the AAP rule "case_manager has full access" across
        BOTH the parent case table and the child case_party table.
      vs ../acl/x_[scope]_case_task_read_manager.xml (manager READ on
      sibling case_task table):
        - <name>          x_[scope]_case_party
                                            vs x_[scope]_case_task
        - <sys_id>        eebbc1bbf1aeab598e7ba377e1e6604b
                                            vs c97e1d074ba86bf16b3a10cb4851e562
        - <sys_update_name> *_case_party_read_manager
                                            vs *_case_task_read_manager
        - <description>                     references case_party table
                                            vs case_task table
        Both ACLs have identical <operation>=read,
        <roles>=x_[scope]_case_manager, <advanced>=false,
        <condition/>=empty, <script/>=empty - the only differences are
        the table name (case_party vs case_task) and the deterministic
        sys_id derived from that table name. This parallelism completes
        the "case_manager has full access" mirror across all three
        custom tables (case, case_task, case_party).
      All other XML elements are identical between the manager-tier ACLs;
      the deterministic sys_id, the table name, and the operation/role
      triplet are the defining differences.

    Cross-dependencies and Update-Set ordering (AAP Section 0.5.2):
      MUST be loaded AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_app/x_[scope]_case_management.xml (scoped app record)
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml (scope record - resolves
          sys_scope and sys_package source="x_[scope]")
        - ../tables/x_[scope]_case_party.xml (resolves
